---
import SiteLayout from '../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro';

const schema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@graph": [
    {
      "@type": "Article",
      "headline": "Building & Maintaining Your Home's Exterior",
      "name": "Building & Maintaining Your Home's Exterior",
      "url": "https://ijustwantto.live/guide-exterior-complete",
      "description": "A complete guide to home exterior projects: decks, fences, stairs, roofing — planning, materials, building codes, and cost estimates.",
      "author": {
        "@type": "Organization",
        "name": "GAB Ventures",
        "url": "https://gab.ae"
      },
      "publisher": {
        "@type": "Organization",
        "name": "ijustwantto.live",
        "logo": {
          "@type": "ImageObject",
          "url": "https://ijustwantto.live/logo.png"
        }
      },
      "datePublished": "2025-01-01",
      "dateModified": "2025-01-01"
    },
    {
      "@type": "FAQPage",
      "mainEntity": [
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is the correct spacing for deck boards?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "For pressure-treated wood decking, a common spacing is 1/8 inch (often the width of a 16d nail) to allow for expansion and drainage. For composite decking, follow the manufacturer's guidelines, which are typically between 3/16 and 1/4 inch."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How deep should fence posts be buried?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "As a general rule, one-third of a fence post's total length should be buried in the ground. For example, a 6-foot fence using an 8-foot post requires a 2-foot deep hole. In colder climates, holes must also extend below the local frost line to prevent heaving."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What are the basic IRC building code requirements for stairs?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "The International Residential Code (IRC) generally requires a maximum riser height of 7 ¾ inches and a minimum tread depth of 10 inches. Additionally, all risers in a flight of stairs must be uniform, varying by no more than 3/8 inch."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Pressure-treated wood vs. composite: which lasts longer?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Composite decking significantly outlasts traditional pressure-treated wood. While wood may last 10–15 years and requires regular staining and sealing, composite decking can last 25–30 years or more with minimal maintenance, though it has a higher initial cost."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How does roof pitch affect the roofing materials I can use?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Roof pitch (rise over run) determines how effectively a roof sheds water. Asphalt shingles generally require a minimum pitch of 2:12 (with special underlayment) or 4:12 (standard). Flat or very low-slope roofs (below 2:12) require seamless membranes like EPDM or TPO to prevent water pooling and leaks."
          }
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
};
---

<SiteLayout
  site="ijustwantto"
  title="Building & Maintaining Your Home's Exterior"
  description="A complete guide to home exterior projects: decks, fences, stairs, roofing — planning, materials, building codes, and cost estimates."
  canonical="https://ijustwantto.live/guide-exterior-complete"
  schema={schema}
>
  <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-5 py-12 text-[var(--text-primary)]">
    <header class="text-center mb-12">
      <h1 class="text-3xl md:text-5xl font-extrabold text-[var(--text-primary)] mb-4 tracking-tight">Building & Maintaining Your Home's Exterior</h1>
      <p class="text-xl text-[var(--text-secondary)] max-w-2xl mx-auto">A complete guide to planning, building, and estimating outdoor projects: decks, fences, stairs, and roofing.</p>
    </header>

    <div class="space-y-10">
      <!-- 1. Planning -->
      <section class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-2xl p-6 md:p-8 shadow-sm">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-[var(--accent-color)] mb-4 border-b border-[var(--border-color)] pb-3">1. Planning Exterior Projects</h2>
        <div class="prose prose-invert max-w-none text-[var(--text-secondary)]">
          <p class="mb-4">Before digging a single hole or swinging a hammer, proper planning is essential for any exterior project. This phase saves time, prevents costly mistakes, and ensures the safety and legality of your build.</p>
          <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4 space-y-2">
            <li><strong class="text-white">Permits and Codes:</strong> Most structural exterior projects, including decks over a certain height (often 30 inches) or fences over 6 feet, require a building permit from your local municipality. Always check your local zoning laws, property lines, and Homeowners Association (HOA) regulations.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-white">Utility Lines:</strong> Call 811 (in the US) or your local utility marking service before you dig to avoid hitting buried gas, water, or electrical lines.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-white">Hiring vs. DIY:</strong> While building a fence or a ground-level deck can be a rewarding DIY project, complex tasks like structural stairs, multi-level decks, or extensive roofing often require the expertise and insurance of licensed contractors. Evaluate your skills honestly.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- 2. Deck Building -->
      <section class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-2xl p-6 md:p-8 shadow-sm">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-[var(--accent-color)] mb-4 border-b border-[var(--border-color)] pb-3">2. Deck Building</h2>
        <div class="prose prose-invert max-w-none text-[var(--text-secondary)]">
          <p class="mb-4">A well-built deck extends your living space outdoors. The foundation of any good deck starts below ground and relies on strong connections to the house.</p>
          <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4 space-y-2">
            <li><strong class="text-white">Footings and Ledger Board:</strong> Deck footings must extend below the frost line to prevent seasonal heaving. The ledger board (where the deck attaches to the house) is a critical failure point; it must be flashed correctly to prevent water intrusion and rot, and bolted—never just nailed—to the house framing.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-white">Materials — Pressure-Treated vs. Composite:</strong> Pressure-treated pine is the most affordable option but requires regular cleaning, staining, and sealing to prevent splintering and rot. Composite decking (made from wood fibers and recycled plastics) costs significantly more upfront but offers decades of low-maintenance durability and is resistant to rot and insects.</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="bg-[var(--bg-color)] p-4 rounded-lg mt-4 border border-[var(--border-color)]">
            <span class="text-white font-semibold">Pro Tip:</span> Planning your material list? Use our <a href="/deck-calculator" class="text-[var(--accent-color)] hover:underline font-bold">Deck Board Calculator</a> to estimate the exact number of decking boards, joists, and screws you need, complete with a 10% waste factor.
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- 3. Fence Installation -->
      <section class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-2xl p-6 md:p-8 shadow-sm">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-[var(--accent-color)] mb-4 border-b border-[var(--border-color)] pb-3">3. Fence Installation</h2>
        <div class="prose prose-invert max-w-none text-[var(--text-secondary)]">
          <p class="mb-4">Whether for privacy, security, or aesthetics, a sturdy fence relies on properly set posts and accurate spacing.</p>
          <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4 space-y-2">
            <li><strong class="text-white">Post Spacing and Footings:</strong> Standard fence posts are typically spaced 6 to 8 feet apart. For a secure anchor, bury one-third of the post's total length in concrete, bell-shaping the bottom of the hole for maximum resistance against frost heave.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-white">Privacy vs. Decorative:</strong> Privacy fences use zero spacing between pickets, blocking wind and lines of sight. Decorative fences (like picket or split-rail) have wider gaps. When building a privacy fence, consider a "shadowbox" design that allows wind to pass through, reducing stress on the posts.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-white">Gate Sizing:</strong> Standard pedestrian gates are 3 to 4 feet wide. Ensure gate posts are set deeper and with more concrete than standard line posts to support the swinging weight.</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="bg-[var(--bg-color)] p-4 rounded-lg mt-4 border border-[var(--border-color)]">
            <span class="text-white font-semibold">Ready to build?</span> Our <a href="/fence-calculator" class="text-[var(--accent-color)] hover:underline font-bold">Fence Calculator</a> helps you determine exactly how many posts, rails, pickets, and bags of concrete you'll need for your layout.
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- 4. Stairs & Steps -->
      <section class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-2xl p-6 md:p-8 shadow-sm">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-[var(--accent-color)] mb-4 border-b border-[var(--border-color)] pb-3">4. Stairs & Steps</h2>
        <div class="prose prose-invert max-w-none text-[var(--text-secondary)]">
          <p class="mb-4">Building stairs requires precise math. Even a minor miscalculation can result in a tripping hazard.</p>
          <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4 space-y-2">
            <li><strong class="text-white">IRC Code Requirements:</strong> For safety, the International Residential Code dictates a maximum riser height (the vertical part) of 7 ¾ inches and a minimum tread depth (the horizontal part you step on) of 10 inches. Consistency is key; riser heights cannot vary by more than 3/8 of an inch across the entire flight.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-white">Stringer Cutting:</strong> The stringer is the notched structural 2x12 that supports the treads. Cutting stringers is an exact science that requires accounting for the thickness of the tread material to ensure the first and last steps meet the ground and landing perfectly.</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="bg-[var(--bg-color)] p-4 rounded-lg mt-4 border border-[var(--border-color)]">
            <span class="text-white font-semibold">Don't guess the math:</span> Use the <a href="/stair-calculator" class="text-[var(--accent-color)] hover:underline font-bold">Stair Calculator</a> to find your exact rise, run, and required stringer length while checking against building codes.
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- 5. Roofing Basics -->
      <section class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-2xl p-6 md:p-8 shadow-sm">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-[var(--accent-color)] mb-4 border-b border-[var(--border-color)] pb-3">5. Roofing Basics</h2>
        <div class="prose prose-invert max-w-none text-[var(--text-secondary)]">
          <p class="mb-4">The roof is your home's primary defense against the elements. Understanding its geometry is vital for maintenance and material estimation.</p>
          <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4 space-y-2">
            <li><strong class="text-white">Pitch Measurement:</strong> Roof pitch is expressed as a ratio of vertical rise over 12 inches of horizontal run. A 6:12 pitch means the roof rises 6 inches for every foot it goes inward.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-white">Material by Pitch:</strong> The pitch dictates what materials are viable. Asphalt shingles generally require at least a 2:12 pitch. Flat roofs (less than 2:12) require continuous waterproof membranes, while very steep roofs may benefit from metal or slate.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-white">Ventilation:</strong> A healthy roof breathes. Proper intake (soffit) and exhaust (ridge) ventilation prevent moisture buildup in the attic, protecting insulation and preventing ice dams in winter.</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="bg-[var(--bg-color)] p-4 rounded-lg mt-4 border border-[var(--border-color)]">
            <span class="text-white font-semibold">Calculate your slope:</span> Our <a href="/roof-pitch" class="text-[var(--accent-color)] hover:underline font-bold">Roof Pitch Calculator</a> converts your rise and run into a ratio, degrees, and calculates the true surface area.
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- 6. Square Footage -->
      <section class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-2xl p-6 md:p-8 shadow-sm">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-[var(--accent-color)] mb-4 border-b border-[var(--border-color)] pb-3">6. Square Footage for Exterior Projects</h2>
        <div class="prose prose-invert max-w-none text-[var(--text-secondary)]">
          <p class="mb-4">From buying mulch and sod to ordering concrete for a patio, accurately measuring area is the foundation of material estimating.</p>
          <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4 space-y-2">
            <li><strong class="text-white">Irregular Shapes:</strong> Not every yard or patio is a perfect rectangle. To find the area of complex spaces, break them down into basic shapes (rectangles, triangles, circles), calculate each separately, and sum the results.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-white">Slope Adjustments:</strong> Remember that a sloped yard or a pitched roof has more surface area than its flat, two-dimensional footprint. This multiplier effect must be calculated to order enough siding, roofing, or landscaping fabric.</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="bg-[var(--bg-color)] p-4 rounded-lg mt-4 border border-[var(--border-color)]">
            <span class="text-white font-semibold">Need to measure complex shapes?</span> Add rectangles, triangles, and circles together easily with our <a href="/sqft-calculator" class="text-[var(--accent-color)] hover:underline font-bold">Square Footage Calculator</a>.
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- 7. Cost Estimation -->
      <section class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-2xl p-6 md:p-8 shadow-sm">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-[var(--accent-color)] mb-4 border-b border-[var(--border-color)] pb-3">7. Cost Estimation</h2>
        <div class="prose prose-invert max-w-none text-[var(--text-secondary)]">
          <p class="mb-4">Exterior projects are significant investments. When estimating costs, be sure to account for both materials and labor if you aren't doing the work yourself.</p>
          <div class="overflow-x-auto mt-4">
            <table class="w-full text-left border-collapse">
              <thead>
                <tr class="border-b border-[var(--border-color)] bg-[var(--bg-color)]">
                  <th class="p-3 text-white font-semibold">Project Type</th>
                  <th class="p-3 text-white font-semibold">Material Estimate</th>
                  <th class="p-3 text-white font-semibold">Labor Considerations</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr class="border-b border-[var(--border-color)] hover:bg-black/20 transition-colors">
                  <td class="p-3 text-white font-medium">Wood Decking</td>
                  <td class="p-3 text-[var(--text-secondary)]">$15 - $30 per sq. ft.</td>
                  <td class="p-3 text-[var(--text-secondary)]">High labor for footings and structural framing.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr class="border-b border-[var(--border-color)] hover:bg-black/20 transition-colors">
                  <td class="p-3 text-white font-medium">Composite Decking</td>
                  <td class="p-3 text-[var(--text-secondary)]">$30 - $60+ per sq. ft.</td>
                  <td class="p-3 text-[var(--text-secondary)]">Similar labor to wood, higher material cost.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr class="border-b border-[var(--border-color)] hover:bg-black/20 transition-colors">
                  <td class="p-3 text-white font-medium">Wood Fencing</td>
                  <td class="p-3 text-[var(--text-secondary)]">$15 - $25 per linear ft.</td>
                  <td class="p-3 text-[var(--text-secondary)]">Post hole digging is the primary labor cost.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr class="border-b border-[var(--border-color)] hover:bg-black/20 transition-colors">
                  <td class="p-3 text-white font-medium">Asphalt Roofing</td>
                  <td class="p-3 text-[var(--text-secondary)]">$350 - $550 per square (100 sq. ft.)</td>
                  <td class="p-3 text-[var(--text-secondary)]">Includes tear-off of old roof and disposal.</td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>
          <p class="mt-4 text-sm italic">* Note: Prices are estimates and vary wildly by region, current lumber prices, and material quality. Always add a 10-15% contingency buffer to your final budget.</p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- 8. FAQ -->
      <section class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-2xl p-6 md:p-8 shadow-sm">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-[var(--accent-color)] mb-6 border-b border-[var(--border-color)] pb-3">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <div class="space-y-6">
          <div>
            <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-white mb-2">What is the correct spacing for deck boards?</h3>
            <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] leading-relaxed">For pressure-treated wood decking, a common spacing is 1/8 inch (often the width of a 16d nail) to allow for expansion and drainage. For composite decking, follow the manufacturer's guidelines, which are typically between 3/16 and 1/4 inch.</p>
          </div>
          <div>
            <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-white mb-2">How deep should fence posts be buried?</h3>
            <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] leading-relaxed">As a general rule, one-third of a fence post's total length should be buried in the ground. For example, a 6-foot fence using an 8-foot post requires a 2-foot deep hole. In colder climates, holes must also extend below the local frost line to prevent heaving.</p>
          </div>
          <div>
            <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-white mb-2">What are the basic IRC building code requirements for stairs?</h3>
            <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] leading-relaxed">The International Residential Code (IRC) generally requires a maximum riser height of 7 ¾ inches and a minimum tread depth of 10 inches. Additionally, all risers in a flight of stairs must be uniform, varying by no more than 3/8 inch.</p>
          </div>
          <div>
            <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-white mb-2">Pressure-treated wood vs. composite: which lasts longer?</h3>
            <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] leading-relaxed">Composite decking significantly outlasts traditional pressure-treated wood. While wood may last 10–15 years and requires regular staining and sealing, composite decking can last 25–30 years or more with minimal maintenance, though it has a higher initial cost.</p>
          </div>
          <div>
            <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-white mb-2">How does roof pitch affect the roofing materials I can use?</h3>
            <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] leading-relaxed">Roof pitch (rise over run) determines how effectively a roof sheds water. Asphalt shingles generally require a minimum pitch of 2:12 (with special underlayment) or 4:12 (standard). Flat or very low-slope roofs (below 2:12) require seamless membranes like EPDM or TPO to prevent water pooling and leaks.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

    </div>
  </div>
</SiteLayout>
